s. inter omnis. All animals, says Aristotle (E. N. VIII, 1, 5 3) have a natural feeling of fellowship with their own kind, but this is especially the case with man, as may be observed more particularly in travelling. Those who are distinguished above the rest for this feeling are called φιλάνθρωποι, and the feeling itself is φιλανθρωπία. The closer feeling which anites, or should unite, members of the same community is termed ὁμόνοια. Both come under the generis term φιλία, though this is used also in a narrower sense for the ‘caritas aut inter duos aut inter paucos’ mentioned below.
